11.8.1 	require the concerned implementing offices the prompt implementation of all projects/programs funded out of the tobacco excise tax in order to give the constituents, especially the tobacco farmers the early benefits that could be derived therefrom;
11.8.2 	advise the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC), all offices in-charge of the implementation together with the Municipal Accountant to determine the total unexpended balances of the completed and the projects which are no longer viable and inform the LCE for possible reappropriation and the latter to recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan for possible reappropriation. Thus, funds could be used fully in accordance with the authorized uses as prescribed in RA Nos. 7171 and 8240;
11.8.3 	ensure that only feasible programs/projects/activities are included in the Annual Investment Program; and
11.8.4 	require regular monitoring of implementation as a basis in taking appropriate action.

13.6	We recommended that the LCE enforce the collection of these taxes, and:
require the Municipal Treasurer to exert more efforts to collect from the taxpayers and for those who have been unable to pay their taxes for several years, issue notices of delinquency for them to settle their unpaid taxes;
if circumstances warrant, avail of the Civil remedies provided for by the provisions of the Local Government Code (RA 7160), specifically Sections 174 to 176 thereof. Section 174 provides for the civil remedies which are by (a) administrative action through distraint of personal properties and (b) by judicial actions.  Section 175 provides for the procedure on the distraint of personal property and Section 176 provides for the levy of Real Properties.

We recommended that the procuring entity strictly adhere to the pertinent provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR to ensure transparency and accountability in the procurement process. We specifically recommended that:

a.	The end-user or implementing unit prepare the Technical Specifications as one of the preparatory documents for procurement activity and submit the same to the BAC for review which shall form part of the bidding documents;

b.	The BAC comply with the posting requirement to ensure timely dissemination of the procurement opportunity. Moreover, invite in writing a representative from a duly recognized private group in all stages of the procurement activities and ensure that the invitations to the three observers are received within the prescribed period. Further, adopt the required procedures and conditions in the Post-Qualification stage particularly in the verification, validation and ascertainment of all statements made and documents submitted by the bidder with the Lowest Calculated Bid to ensure that they are in accordance with the requirements as stated in the Bidding Documents;

c.	The Municipal Engineering Office integrate the Construction Safety and Health Program (CSHP) in the computation of project’s construction cost of all projects to be implemented to ensure the protection and welfare of the public within the vicinity of the worksite;


d.	The LCE require the submission of duly accomplished and valid performance security prior to the signing of contract agreement to guarantee faithful performance by the winning bidder of his obligations under the contract in accordance with the Bidding Documents;

e.	The BAC, through its Secretariat, see to it that the NOA, NTP and a copy of the approved contract were posted in the PhilGEPS website within three (3) and fifteen (15) calendar days from their respective issuances for information purposes.

We recommended that the procuring entity strictly adhere to the pertinent provisions of the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations to ensure transparency and accountability in the procurement process. We specifically recommended that:
The end-user or implementing unit prepare the Technical Specifications as one of the preparatory documents for procurement activity and submit the same to the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) for review which shall form part of the bidding documents;
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) comply with the posting requirement to ensure timely dissemination of the procurement opportunity.  Moreover, invite in writing a representative from a duly recognized private group in all stages of the procurement activities and ensure that the invitations to the three observers are received within the prescribed period. Further, adopt the required procedures and conditions in the Post-Qualification stage particularly in the verification, validation and ascertainment of all statements made and documents submitted by the bidder with the Lowest Calculated Bid to ensure that they are in accordance with the requirements as stated in the Bidding Documents;
The Municipal Engineering Office integrate the Construction Safety and Health Program (CSHP) in the computation of project’s construction cost of all projects to be implemented to ensure the protection and welfare of the public within the vicinity of the worksite;
The Local Chief Executive require the submission of duly accomplished and valid performance security prior to the signing of contract agreement to guarantee faithful performance by the winning bidder of his obligations under the contract in accordance with the Bidding Documents;
The BAC, though its Secretariat, see to it that the Notice of Award, Notice to Proceed and a copy of the approved contract were posted in the PhilGEPS website within three (3) and fifteen (15) calendar days from their respective issuances for information purposes.

In order to rectify the foregoing deficiencies, we have recommended that:

a). the BAC Chairman  instruct the heads of requisitioning offices to avoid indicating the brand name of  items being requested in the Purchase Request and the BAC Secretariat in the Request for Quotation, except for replacement of parts of equipment.  Instead, indicate the complete specifications of the items; 

b). the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Chairman   require the BAC Secretariat to post the Notice of Award in the Philgeps and website of the procuring entity within three (3) calendar days from its issuance and the Notice to Proceed and awarded contracts within fifteen (15) calendar days from issuance of the Notice to Proceed;

c). management  require future contractors to submit  duly accomplished performance security with a validity period that include the one year defects liability period pursuant to Section 39 of the IRR of RA 9184. The validity period shall commence from the effectivity of the contract up to after one year from date of completion of the project or until the issuance of the Certificate of Acceptance.  Moreover, the Municipal Accountant being the internal auditor of the municipality should see to it that all supporting documents of disbursement vouchers are properly accomplished to ensure validity and legality of the transactions.

d). management  require future contractors to post warranty security after the defects liability period of one year from project completion.  Such security must be in accordance with the schedules prescribed in Sections 62.2.3.2 and 62.2.3.3 of the RIRR of RA 9184.

